00:01:33.720 --> 00:01:41.440
So today's lecture is this part.

00:01:41.440 --> 00:01:44.380
We'll have three topics.

00:01:44.380 --> 00:01:51.360
One is I want to provide a
motivation for single quantum

00:01:51.360 --> 00:01:53.440
systems.

00:01:53.440 --> 00:01:54.980
And you should appreciate this.

00:01:54.980 --> 00:01:59.250
A single quantum system is not
what Schrodinger and Heisenberg

00:01:59.250 --> 00:02:00.620
told us about.

00:02:00.620 --> 00:02:03.866
Quantum mechanics was formulated
as an ensemble average.

00:02:03.866 --> 00:02:10.240
But today we want to talk about,
is there something in addition?

00:02:10.240 --> 00:02:13.060
About single quantum systems.

00:02:13.060 --> 00:02:19.730
Part two is-- addresses the
derivation of the quantum Monte

00:02:19.730 --> 00:02:22.220
Carlo wave function method.

00:02:22.220 --> 00:02:24.650
And this is a formalism,
which is really

00:02:24.650 --> 00:02:28.250
simulating in quite general
terms, quantum physics

00:02:28.250 --> 00:02:31.630
by following-- using quantum
Monte Carlo simulations--

00:02:31.630 --> 00:02:34.250
trajectories of individual
quantum systems.

00:02:34.250 --> 00:02:36.990
So here the individual
quantum system--

00:02:36.990 --> 00:02:39.960
even if you have one, even
if you don't have one--

00:02:39.960 --> 00:02:43.120
becomes a computational tool.

00:02:43.120 --> 00:02:46.080
And eventually in
part two I want

00:02:46.080 --> 00:02:49.620
to give you another example
for unraveling open quantum

00:02:49.620 --> 00:02:56.540
system, which differ from
the models for dephasing.

00:02:56.540 --> 00:03:00.580
And if you remember that this
was on one of your homework

00:03:00.580 --> 00:03:02.000
assignment that's correct.

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:04.210
I sort of want to here
take your homework

00:03:04.210 --> 00:03:08.100
into the classroom discussion.

00:03:08.100 --> 00:03:11.070
Well I think it's nice to start
this lecture with the quote

00:03:11.070 --> 00:03:13.832
by Erwin Schrodinger.

00:03:13.832 --> 00:03:16.550
Where he said, "We
never experiment

00:03:16.550 --> 00:03:19.370
with just one electron,
or atom, or molecule.

00:03:19.370 --> 00:03:23.600
In thought experiments, we
sometimes assume that we do;

00:03:23.600 --> 00:03:28.700
this inevitably entails
ridiculous consequences."

00:03:28.700 --> 00:03:32.670
Well today we want to talk about
those ridiculous consequences,

00:03:32.670 --> 00:03:37.380
because many people
in our field trap,

00:03:37.380 --> 00:03:41.255
address, and observe single
electrons and single atoms.

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:48.630
Now this is related
to quantum jumps.

00:03:48.630 --> 00:03:53.770
Quantum jumps has even made
it into the popular realm.

00:03:53.770 --> 00:03:58.050
You can find lots and lots of
references on quantum jumping,

00:03:58.050 --> 00:04:00.610
but I warn you this
is about quantum

00:04:00.610 --> 00:04:02.810
jumping into different worlds.

00:04:02.810 --> 00:04:05.770
It's about broadening
your horizon.

00:04:05.770 --> 00:04:08.640
And those authors,
those people actually,

00:04:08.640 --> 00:04:12.780
sell you something by claiming
that people like Einstein

00:04:12.780 --> 00:04:17.480
and Stephen Hawking would
support the idea that you can

00:04:17.480 --> 00:04:21.640
jump into different universe,
experience another version

00:04:21.640 --> 00:04:24.920
of yourself-- probably a
better version of yourself--

00:04:24.920 --> 00:04:27.110
and this will
inspire you to change

00:04:27.110 --> 00:04:29.880
your life in the world you live.

00:04:29.880 --> 00:04:31.750
But-- So this is
quantum jumping.

00:04:31.750 --> 00:04:33.810
I'm not talking about
quantum jumping,

00:04:33.810 --> 00:04:37.780
I will only talk
about quantum chunks.

00:04:37.780 --> 00:04:44.150
So what you see here is
really a classic experiment.

00:04:44.150 --> 00:04:45.910
One of three
experiments which were

00:04:45.910 --> 00:04:47.820
done almost simultaneously.

00:04:47.820 --> 00:04:49.620
There have always been
races for, you know,

00:04:49.620 --> 00:04:51.170
the first observation
of something.

00:04:51.170 --> 00:04:53.880
And there was the [? Hamburg ?]
group by [? Toshak ?],

00:04:53.880 --> 00:04:56.150
the Seattle group
by Hunt [INAUDIBLE],

00:04:56.150 --> 00:04:59.000
and the Boulder
Group by Dave Wylen,

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:02.580
who observed the phenomenon
of quantum jumps for the first

00:05:02.580 --> 00:05:03.310
time.

00:05:03.310 --> 00:05:05.190
Let me just tell you
what it is, because it's

00:05:05.190 --> 00:05:07.780
exactly what you're
going to describe.

00:05:07.780 --> 00:05:11.500
Here in this situation
you have a system.

00:05:11.500 --> 00:05:15.560
It's a trapped barium
ion with a p and s state.

00:05:15.560 --> 00:05:19.970
And there is very
fast transition

00:05:19.970 --> 00:05:22.370
where you can rapidly
scatter light, and get

00:05:22.370 --> 00:05:25.605
lots of fluorescence,
at 493 nanometer.

00:05:28.200 --> 00:05:33.870
But what happened is,
every once in a while,

00:05:33.870 --> 00:05:44.520
the particle has a branching
ratio to decay to d state,

00:05:44.520 --> 00:05:50.310
and, well, d to s 2 units
of angular momentum.

00:05:50.310 --> 00:05:55.910
The transition here down to
the ground state is very slow.

00:05:55.910 --> 00:05:57.930
It's slow because
it's forbidden.

00:05:57.930 --> 00:06:00.950
It's even slower
because it happens

00:06:00.950 --> 00:06:05.980
at longer wavelengths
of 1,600 nanometer.

00:06:05.980 --> 00:06:07.190
And this is slow.

00:06:07.190 --> 00:06:12.340
And it has a lifetime
of about 50 second.

00:06:12.340 --> 00:06:17.580
So you-- If you think
about it naively

00:06:17.580 --> 00:06:19.370
and that's probably
the correct approach--

00:06:19.370 --> 00:06:21.970
you would say the
particles in the s state,

00:06:21.970 --> 00:06:23.140
it's like a light bulb.

00:06:23.140 --> 00:06:26.210
It scatters many, many
photons, but then it

00:06:26.210 --> 00:06:28.030
branches to the d state.

00:06:28.030 --> 00:06:30.210
And for 50 seconds
the light bulb

00:06:30.210 --> 00:06:33.410
is switched off, until
the particle spontaneously

00:06:33.410 --> 00:06:35.710
goes down to the s state,
and then the light bulb

00:06:35.710 --> 00:06:37.420
is switched on.

00:06:37.420 --> 00:06:40.100
And this is exactly
what people observed.

00:06:40.100 --> 00:06:42.469
But I mean I was-- This was '86.

00:06:42.469 --> 00:06:44.260
That was the time I
was a graduate student,

00:06:44.260 --> 00:06:46.190
and I talked with
theorists in the field,

00:06:46.190 --> 00:06:48.650
and respectable
theorists told me

00:06:48.650 --> 00:06:50.640
that there was a
controversy-- probably

00:06:50.640 --> 00:06:53.250
not among experimentalists,
who use the naive

00:06:53.250 --> 00:06:55.890
approach-- but theorists
who believed too much

00:06:55.890 --> 00:06:57.990
in what they calculate.

00:06:57.990 --> 00:07:00.380
Because if you solve it
quantum mechanically,

00:07:00.380 --> 00:07:02.060
and look what you get.

00:07:02.060 --> 00:07:03.730
It's a steady state solution.

00:07:03.730 --> 00:07:04.670
Atom in steady state.

00:07:04.670 --> 00:07:06.020
Laser in steady state.

00:07:06.020 --> 00:07:09.560
And if you calculate the quantum
mechanical expectation value,

00:07:09.560 --> 00:07:13.030
the expectation value is
constant as a function of time.

00:07:13.030 --> 00:07:15.420
So a simple quantum
calculation would

00:07:15.420 --> 00:07:18.740
say the fluorescence
is on average.

00:07:18.740 --> 00:07:20.940
Well just the time
average and his constant,

00:07:20.940 --> 00:07:22.770
and his time independent.

00:07:22.770 --> 00:07:25.190
So there were some
serious doubts

00:07:25.190 --> 00:07:27.650
whether you would observe
this, or something

00:07:27.650 --> 00:07:30.840
which looks more like
the ensemble average.

00:07:30.840 --> 00:07:35.260
Well made all of the theorists
soon realize you cannot

00:07:35.260 --> 00:07:37.510
calculate the steady
state average.

00:07:37.510 --> 00:07:40.080
You have to calculate
the correlation function

00:07:40.080 --> 00:07:41.080
in steady state.

00:07:41.080 --> 00:07:43.190
And the steady state
correlation function

00:07:43.190 --> 00:07:45.940
has structure exactly
at 50 seconds.

00:07:45.940 --> 00:07:48.590
So in a steady state
system, if you're

00:07:48.590 --> 00:07:51.760
interested in fluctuations
and temporal behavior,

00:07:51.760 --> 00:07:54.320
you can't just
calculate quantities,

00:07:54.320 --> 00:07:57.530
you have to calculate
correlation functions

00:07:57.530 --> 00:07:59.250
of quantities.

00:07:59.250 --> 00:08:02.110
So anyway-- But then
of course, if you now

00:08:02.110 --> 00:08:05.270
average over many,
many realizations,

00:08:05.270 --> 00:08:09.730
you find exactly an exponential
decay of 50 seconds.

00:08:09.730 --> 00:08:11.660
And this is sort
of what you would

00:08:11.660 --> 00:08:14.970
get for an ensemble average.

00:08:14.970 --> 00:08:17.200
So this is what
quantum jumps are.

00:08:17.200 --> 00:08:19.090
This is what you
should always imagine

00:08:19.090 --> 00:08:23.340
when we talk about quantum jumps
in the rest of this lecture.

00:08:23.340 --> 00:08:25.910
But I also want to show
you more recent example

00:08:25.910 --> 00:08:29.520
from Serge Haroche,
in Paris, where

00:08:29.520 --> 00:08:32.860
they observed quantum jumps.

00:08:32.860 --> 00:08:36.520
Recording a single
photon in a cavity.

00:08:36.520 --> 00:08:39.750
So what happens is there's a
single photon in this cavity,

00:08:39.750 --> 00:08:41.730
and they can read
out whether there

00:08:41.730 --> 00:08:45.230
is a photon or not by sending
Rydberg atoms through.

00:08:45.230 --> 00:08:48.210
And a single photon
is never observed,

00:08:48.210 --> 00:08:51.640
but it causes a phase
shift, an AC-Stark shift,

00:08:51.640 --> 00:08:53.330
on the Rydberg atom.

00:08:53.330 --> 00:08:56.010
And then they can read out
with a Ramsey interferometer

00:08:56.010 --> 00:08:57.750
the AC-Stark shift.

00:08:57.750 --> 00:09:01.080
So every atom which
passes through the cavity

00:09:01.080 --> 00:09:04.910
will tell you whether
there is a photon or not.

00:09:04.910 --> 00:09:08.740
And-- And this is shown here.

00:09:08.740 --> 00:09:12.830
Blue means no,
there is no photon.

00:09:12.830 --> 00:09:14.720
Red means there is a photon.

00:09:14.720 --> 00:09:18.850
So here you repeatedly figure
out again there is no photon.

00:09:18.850 --> 00:09:21.060
And suddenly there
is a quantum jump

00:09:21.060 --> 00:09:23.455
when the cavity has
absorbed a photon,

00:09:23.455 --> 00:09:26.750
or when a thermal
photon was released.

00:09:26.750 --> 00:09:29.060
You may say, what happened here?

00:09:29.060 --> 00:09:30.640
Well no measurement is perfect.

00:09:30.640 --> 00:09:31.680
There is some noise.

00:09:31.680 --> 00:09:33.910
But by seeing that
these are outliers,

00:09:33.910 --> 00:09:37.250
you clearly see that here
is a photon in the cavity,

00:09:37.250 --> 00:09:42.030
and here where the red
read out of the atom

00:09:42.030 --> 00:09:45.610
overwhelms the blue readout
here you have no photon.

00:09:45.610 --> 00:09:50.690
And then as time goes by, you
can observe the death and birth

00:09:50.690 --> 00:09:54.450
of micro-cavity photons.

00:09:54.450 --> 00:09:57.320
So these are now quantum
jumps in the-- not

00:09:57.320 --> 00:10:01.400
in atomic population, but
quantum jumps in the photon

00:10:01.400 --> 00:10:04.814
number in a cavity.

00:10:04.814 --> 00:10:07.244
AUDIENCE:What's the
time scale on that?

00:10:07.244 --> 00:10:09.200
Seconds?

00:10:09.200 --> 00:10:10.710
PROFESSOR: Yeah, time is second.

00:10:10.710 --> 00:10:15.940
So what is shown here is-- I
think what is shown is here

00:10:15.940 --> 00:10:22.955
are 300 milliseconds, and
this is 2.5 second element.

00:10:22.955 --> 00:10:26.210
AUDIENCE: What was the
density of each line mean?

00:10:26.210 --> 00:10:29.350
PROFESSOR: Each line
is a Rydberg atom,

00:10:29.350 --> 00:10:32.290
which has been readout with
a Ramsey interferometer.

00:10:32.290 --> 00:10:32.791
And--

00:10:32.791 --> 00:10:34.290
AUDIENCE: So that
means that they're

00:10:34.290 --> 00:10:35.520
leaving no, like between--

00:10:35.520 --> 00:10:36.978
PROFESSOR: I think
that means there

00:10:36.978 --> 00:10:40.380
was a Rydberg atom in state e,
which means there is a photon.

00:10:40.380 --> 00:10:42.840
And blue means, the
blue bar means, there

00:10:42.840 --> 00:10:45.790
was a Rydberg atom in state g.

00:10:45.790 --> 00:10:50.340
These are two highlighting
states of the rubidium atom.

00:10:50.340 --> 00:10:52.300
Sort of each spike
here is one readout

00:10:52.300 --> 00:10:55.750
of the microchannel plate.

00:10:55.750 --> 00:10:57.530
So these are detector clicks.

00:10:57.530 --> 00:10:59.180
You can say, yes.

00:10:59.180 --> 00:11:02.322
You can sort of say, blue
is yes, and red is no.

00:11:02.322 --> 00:11:03.530
And these are the two clicks.

00:11:03.530 --> 00:11:06.302
AUDIENCE: Yeah, but, like the
separation between two clicks

00:11:06.302 --> 00:11:07.882
is not uniform.

00:11:07.882 --> 00:11:09.840
PROFESSOR: No, because
if you're an atomic beam

00:11:09.840 --> 00:11:12.600
the atoms come not
equally spaced out.

00:11:12.600 --> 00:11:14.700
There's a randomness
when the atom comes.

00:11:14.700 --> 00:11:18.700
I think it's posed only in
statistics in this experiment.

00:11:18.700 --> 00:11:19.790
It's a real experiment.

00:11:19.790 --> 00:11:21.184
It's amazing.

00:11:21.184 --> 00:11:21.850
Other questions?

00:11:21.850 --> 00:11:22.380
Team One.

