00:12:59.710 --> 00:13:03.100
And the little overlap, there
is maybe a little bit of time

00:13:03.100 --> 00:13:05.970
where you don't know whether
there is a photon or not.

00:13:05.970 --> 00:13:10.410
But this really-- This is
real, because every measurement

00:13:10.410 --> 00:13:12.560
takes a certain amount of time.

00:13:12.560 --> 00:13:14.450
Since you have a
few random clicks,

00:13:14.450 --> 00:13:16.125
if they are a few
random clicks, you

00:13:16.125 --> 00:13:19.070
do not know yet if
the system has jumped,

00:13:19.070 --> 00:13:20.960
you have to wait a little bit.

00:13:20.960 --> 00:13:23.075
But this is really
also showing how

00:13:23.075 --> 00:13:28.480
our knowledge about the
quantum system comes with time.

00:13:28.480 --> 00:13:29.880
And therefore,
the wave function,

00:13:29.880 --> 00:13:33.130
or the statistical
operator changes with time,

00:13:33.130 --> 00:13:35.710
because of wave function
and statistical operator

00:13:35.710 --> 00:13:38.950
are simply a description of
our knowledge about the quantum

00:13:38.950 --> 00:13:39.450
system.

00:13:42.372 --> 00:13:47.242
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
is too dense

00:13:55.224 --> 00:13:57.390
PROFESSOR: You could have
a situation, for instance,

00:13:57.390 --> 00:13:59.270
you could prepare
the cavity, that it

00:13:59.270 --> 00:14:01.970
has an equal probability
foreseeable in one.

00:14:01.970 --> 00:14:05.510
And then what you would read out
may just be completely random.

00:14:05.510 --> 00:14:08.200
So that may be possible,
but in their experiment,

00:14:08.200 --> 00:14:12.570
I think, the nature
here is that you

00:14:12.570 --> 00:14:14.410
have most of the
time stable photons,

00:14:14.410 --> 00:14:17.440
because the cavity is cooled
to very low temperature,

00:14:17.440 --> 00:14:21.410
and only occasionally does
the thermal distribution,

00:14:21.410 --> 00:14:23.870
the Bose-Einstein distribution
of photons in the cavity

00:14:23.870 --> 00:14:24.780
have a one.

00:14:24.780 --> 00:14:27.540
And what we observe are
the thermal fluctuations

00:14:27.540 --> 00:14:30.610
between mainly 0 and
occasionally a 1.

00:14:35.250 --> 00:14:38.260
If you would make the cavity
and little bit hotter,

00:14:38.260 --> 00:14:41.320
it would have maybe
half of the time a 1

00:14:41.320 --> 00:14:43.640
and half of the time 0.

00:14:43.640 --> 00:14:46.540
But that wouldn't mean that
you have completely randomness

00:14:46.540 --> 00:14:50.280
in your results, because
there is a thermal relaxation

00:14:50.280 --> 00:14:52.740
time over which a
photon is created,

00:14:52.740 --> 00:14:54.360
and a photon goes back.

00:14:54.360 --> 00:14:57.430
The photon would not jump
back and forth from the cavity

00:14:57.430 --> 00:15:00.290
to the walls of the
cavity in microseconds.

00:15:00.290 --> 00:15:03.600
It would probably
have an exchange time,

00:15:03.600 --> 00:15:06.274
and you could sort of measure
the thermal correlation

00:15:06.274 --> 00:15:07.440
time of photons in a cavity.

00:15:10.150 --> 00:15:11.400
It's a really good experiment.

00:15:15.040 --> 00:15:15.590
OK.

00:15:15.590 --> 00:15:18.550
So in that sense I
think I showed you

00:15:18.550 --> 00:15:23.300
that what Schrodinger said
is ridiculous is real,

00:15:23.300 --> 00:15:26.450
is the subject of
current research,

00:15:26.450 --> 00:15:29.180
and since for
quantum information

00:15:29.180 --> 00:15:30.720
processing in
quantum computers, we

00:15:30.720 --> 00:15:33.830
need single quantum system
is at the heart of quantum

00:15:33.830 --> 00:15:36.220
information processing.

00:15:36.220 --> 00:15:46.410
So therefore, we
want to now describe

00:15:46.410 --> 00:15:47.740
single quantum systems.

00:16:01.090 --> 00:16:04.710
But when I do that,
I-- come very --

00:16:04.710 --> 00:16:06.640
It will become clear at
the end of this unit,

00:16:06.640 --> 00:16:10.790
but I want to give you
the warning right away.

00:16:10.790 --> 00:16:14.630
The way how I describe now
a single quantum system

00:16:14.630 --> 00:16:15.820
may not be unique.

00:16:19.110 --> 00:16:21.660
There will be,
there is actually,

00:16:21.660 --> 00:16:23.420
an infinite number of ways.

00:16:27.330 --> 00:16:29.040
And I've already
mentioned that to you,

00:16:29.040 --> 00:16:31.160
that there is an
infinite number of ways

00:16:31.160 --> 00:16:34.720
to unravel a density matrix.

00:16:34.720 --> 00:16:37.420
I mentioned that you can
write every density matrix

00:16:37.420 --> 00:16:40.380
as a probability of pure states.

00:16:40.380 --> 00:16:42.810
Weighted probability of
being in pure states,

00:16:42.810 --> 00:16:44.417
but there's always
different choices.

00:16:44.417 --> 00:16:46.750
You can get an infinite number
of different combinations

00:16:46.750 --> 00:16:50.320
of pure states, and construct
your density matrix.

00:16:50.320 --> 00:16:53.250
So, so this was sort of in
at the level of the density

00:16:53.250 --> 00:16:56.730
matrix, but similarly--
and this will come out

00:16:56.730 --> 00:17:04.452
of this discussion today--
there is also an infinite number

00:17:04.452 --> 00:17:11.089
of ways to unravel the
dynamics-- the dynamics

00:17:11.089 --> 00:17:14.010
involved in the evolution
of an open quantum system.

00:17:20.630 --> 00:17:28.590
So-- so with that I want to
describe the quantum Monte

00:17:28.590 --> 00:17:30.340
Carlo wave function method.

00:17:33.120 --> 00:17:37.040
So in the quantum Monte
Carlo wave function method,

00:17:37.040 --> 00:17:40.380
we perform-- We don't
need an experiment.

00:17:40.380 --> 00:17:42.490
We don't need
sophisticated experiments

00:17:42.490 --> 00:17:44.280
to observe a single
quantum system.

00:17:44.280 --> 00:17:46.420
It's a theoretical
method, but we

00:17:46.420 --> 00:17:49.115
perform thought, or
gedanken experiments.

00:17:51.700 --> 00:17:57.850
So our gedanken experiments is
that we perform measurements.

00:17:57.850 --> 00:18:05.540
So we assume-- we
have-- When we want

00:18:05.540 --> 00:18:07.180
to describe an
ensemble of atoms,

00:18:07.180 --> 00:18:09.360
we assume we have a single atom.

00:18:09.360 --> 00:18:11.730
We assume it emits
photon, and then we

00:18:11.730 --> 00:18:14.210
assume that the
photon is detected.

00:18:14.210 --> 00:18:17.080
And the mom-- So the
moment the photon

00:18:17.080 --> 00:18:19.380
is detected we
know, for instance,

00:18:19.380 --> 00:18:21.230
that the atom is in
the ground state.

00:18:21.230 --> 00:18:24.830
And so our quantum Monte
Carlo simulation follows now

00:18:24.830 --> 00:18:28.870
the trajectory of the single
quantum system by saying,

00:18:28.870 --> 00:18:31.110
I toss a coin, there's
a certain probability

00:18:31.110 --> 00:18:32.370
for detecting the photon.

00:18:32.370 --> 00:18:34.420
If I detect the photon,
the system I know

00:18:34.420 --> 00:18:35.650
is in the ground state.

00:18:35.650 --> 00:18:37.510
If I don't detect
the photon, it's

00:18:37.510 --> 00:18:39.150
not in the ground
state, and such.

00:18:39.150 --> 00:18:43.080
And these probabilistic
approach is just simulated

00:18:43.080 --> 00:18:46.340
in the quantum
Monte Carlo sense.

00:18:46.340 --> 00:18:49.950
So-- So what is
in essence-- what

00:18:49.950 --> 00:18:51.850
is the essence of the
quantum Monte Carlo

00:18:51.850 --> 00:18:56.900
method is that we allow a
small time step delta t.

00:18:56.900 --> 00:18:59.530
It's a real time simulation.

00:18:59.530 --> 00:19:02.260
And there is a small
probability that the system

00:19:02.260 --> 00:19:05.320
has decayed in that time.

00:19:05.320 --> 00:19:10.840
So we may now toss a coin-- use
a random function generator--

00:19:10.840 --> 00:19:14.695
and ask, has spontaneous
emission taken place?

00:19:17.210 --> 00:19:20.840
And then the two
possibilities are yes,

00:19:20.840 --> 00:19:23.450
and we continue
whatever the outcome,

00:19:23.450 --> 00:19:25.130
whatever the quantum state is.

00:19:25.130 --> 00:19:32.880
Or we say no, and then with
the probability-- with a-- so

00:19:32.880 --> 00:19:35.060
with a probability,
p, we say yes.

00:19:35.060 --> 00:19:37.380
With a probability
1 minus p we say no,

00:19:37.380 --> 00:19:39.710
and then we continue the
simulation accordingly.

00:19:42.500 --> 00:19:44.420
So this will become
much, much clearer

00:19:44.420 --> 00:19:47.200
when I write down the
formalism for you,

00:19:47.200 --> 00:19:51.660
but there is one important
aspect, which I really

00:19:51.660 --> 00:19:52.990
want to discuss with you.

00:19:52.990 --> 00:19:55.420
And this is the
essence of the method.

00:19:55.420 --> 00:19:59.370
Namely, how does
the wave function

00:19:59.370 --> 00:20:00.840
change by your measurement?

00:20:04.450 --> 00:20:09.210
So-- so this is the essential,
the only conceptional part

00:20:09.210 --> 00:20:10.960
for the quantum Monte
Carlo wave function.

00:20:10.960 --> 00:20:12.315
Afterwards I just show you.

00:20:12.315 --> 00:20:14.320
Once you have this,
once we have cleared up

00:20:14.320 --> 00:20:17.340
this conceptional part, the
rest is just a few equations.

00:20:17.340 --> 00:20:20.680
And we immediately show that
the quantum Monte Carlo wave

00:20:20.680 --> 00:20:23.700
function method is equivalent
to the optical block equation.

00:20:23.700 --> 00:20:26.170
But let's really feature
and take some time

00:20:26.170 --> 00:20:30.170
for discussing the concept,
namely, the change over wave

00:20:30.170 --> 00:20:33.060
function by a
quantum measurement.

00:20:36.550 --> 00:20:38.670
And maybe what this
carries home to you

00:20:38.670 --> 00:20:42.730
is that the nature of an open
system-- we have a quantum

00:20:42.730 --> 00:20:45.220
system, which interacts
with the environment--

00:20:45.220 --> 00:20:50.100
is, actually, that the
environment permanently

00:20:50.100 --> 00:20:52.170
performs measurements.

00:20:52.170 --> 00:20:54.890
And you will actually see
that the idea of performing

00:20:54.890 --> 00:20:59.620
measurements, formalized in
the quantum Monte Carlo sense,

00:20:59.620 --> 00:21:02.540
gives us an equation for
the density matrix, which

00:21:02.540 --> 00:21:05.400
is identical to the
optical block equation.

00:21:05.400 --> 00:21:07.550
So in other words, you
can say I am re-deriving

00:21:07.550 --> 00:21:10.780
for you master equation now,
but from a very, very different

00:21:10.780 --> 00:21:11.680
perspective.

00:21:11.680 --> 00:21:14.370
From the perspective
of an environment

00:21:14.370 --> 00:21:16.205
which constantly
performs measurement.

00:21:18.770 --> 00:21:19.270
OK.

00:21:19.270 --> 00:21:21.140
So let's go through that.

00:21:21.140 --> 00:21:25.280
How-- What happens
in a measurement?

00:21:25.280 --> 00:21:33.150
Well if our initial state is
the ground state-- starting

00:21:33.150 --> 00:21:36.400
very in trivial ways-- well
there is no measurement,

00:21:36.400 --> 00:21:39.865
because the particle will stay
in the ground state forever.

00:21:44.660 --> 00:21:45.160
OK.

00:21:45.160 --> 00:21:48.940
Now let's go to
the next situation

00:21:48.940 --> 00:21:52.830
that our atom starts out
in the excited state.

00:21:52.830 --> 00:22:01.140
Now in a time step delta t,
we have two possibilities.

00:22:01.140 --> 00:22:05.460
A photon can be observed,
or nor photon is observed.

00:22:09.720 --> 00:22:15.210
When the photon is
observed, we know for sure

00:22:15.210 --> 00:22:20.130
that the system is now
projected into the ground state.

00:22:20.130 --> 00:22:23.870
If no photon is
observed, well the system

00:22:23.870 --> 00:22:25.320
is still in the excited state.

00:22:27.881 --> 00:22:28.380
OK.

00:22:28.380 --> 00:22:31.092
So we've discussed what happens
when the system is initially

00:22:31.092 --> 00:22:33.050
in the ground, and when
the system is initially

00:22:33.050 --> 00:22:35.280
in the excited state.

00:22:35.280 --> 00:22:39.390
But now comes the
following question.

00:22:39.390 --> 00:22:42.600
We prepare the system
in a superposition

00:22:42.600 --> 00:22:46.820
of ground and excited state.

00:22:46.820 --> 00:22:53.010
And we want to
discuss what happens

00:22:53.010 --> 00:22:54.250
when the photon is observed?

00:22:57.740 --> 00:23:00.970
What happens when no
photon is observed?

00:23:00.970 --> 00:23:04.130
I think if you observe
the photon it's

00:23:04.130 --> 00:23:07.150
pretty clear we have to
assume after photon emission

00:23:07.150 --> 00:23:10.050
the system is in
the ground state.

00:23:10.050 --> 00:23:16.060
But if no photon is observed, I
want to give you three choices,

00:23:16.060 --> 00:23:20.480
and you should address
them with the clicker.

00:23:20.480 --> 00:23:30.010
One choice is that the particle
stays in the same state.

00:23:30.010 --> 00:23:36.440
The second choice is
that the particle stays

00:23:36.440 --> 00:23:40.780
in a superposition state,
but the probability

00:23:40.780 --> 00:23:45.540
to be in the excited
state decays.

00:23:45.540 --> 00:23:47.380
Also no photon
has being emitted,

00:23:47.380 --> 00:23:50.460
or no photon has been observed.

00:23:50.460 --> 00:23:55.020
And the third possibility
is something else.

00:24:01.180 --> 00:24:05.410
So in other words, assume
you're an observer,

00:24:05.410 --> 00:24:08.440
and you know with 100%
detection probability--

00:24:08.440 --> 00:24:11.330
let's not discuss technical
issues-- you have completely

00:24:11.330 --> 00:24:14.410
surrounded your system
with perfect detectors.

00:24:14.410 --> 00:24:18.880
And you know in the time
step delta t, in the time t,

00:24:18.880 --> 00:24:21.200
no photon was observed.

00:24:21.200 --> 00:24:23.240
And now you should
make a prediction

00:24:23.240 --> 00:24:25.240
what happens next to
the quantum system.

00:24:25.240 --> 00:24:27.950
And you make the
prediction by assuming

00:24:27.950 --> 00:24:31.010
that the system is described
by a wave function or density

00:24:31.010 --> 00:24:32.150
matrix.

00:24:32.150 --> 00:24:37.220
And I'm asking you, which
of the three choices

00:24:37.220 --> 00:24:41.760
correctly describes what the
system will do afterwards?

00:24:41.760 --> 00:24:44.900
What the system will do next?

00:24:44.900 --> 00:24:46.910
Is the question very clear?

00:24:46.910 --> 00:24:48.395
Good.

00:24:48.395 --> 00:24:52.355
[TAPPING]

00:24:59.160 --> 00:24:59.660
OK.

00:25:10.013 --> 00:25:11.196
All right.

00:25:11.196 --> 00:25:13.880
Pretty good.

00:25:13.880 --> 00:25:19.520
A lot of people when I taught
the class before said it's A,

00:25:19.520 --> 00:25:21.570
the wave function
is not changing,

00:25:21.570 --> 00:25:24.310
because no photon
has been emitted.

00:25:24.310 --> 00:25:37.150
Now in-- For those people, but
there only few among those,

00:25:37.150 --> 00:25:39.405
I would have now asked
the next question.

00:25:43.380 --> 00:25:55.990
If you have-- If you have
a 50-50 superposition,

00:25:55.990 --> 00:25:59.980
of ground and excited
state-- And let's

00:25:59.980 --> 00:26:03.630
say the spot time for
spontaneous emission

00:26:03.630 --> 00:26:17.150
is 10 nanoseconds-- But
now you wait one second,

00:26:17.150 --> 00:26:23.010
and after 1 second, no
photon has been observed.

00:26:27.120 --> 00:26:28.980
What is your prediction?

00:26:28.980 --> 00:26:33.620
In what state is the
system at this point?

00:26:33.620 --> 00:26:36.030
Is the system in
the ground state?

00:26:36.030 --> 00:26:40.570
Or is the system in,
still in, a superposition

00:26:40.570 --> 00:26:42.090
of ground and excited state?

00:26:45.090 --> 00:26:47.250
Well since we have to
clicker, you can tell me.

00:26:47.250 --> 00:26:49.159
Is it-- Is it still a
superposition state,

00:26:49.159 --> 00:26:50.700
or is the system in
the ground state?

00:27:29.040 --> 00:27:31.020
OK.

00:27:31.020 --> 00:27:36.200
So now you have to help me out,
because the people who said B,

00:27:36.200 --> 00:27:42.410
if they would go back to
here-- And most people said

00:27:42.410 --> 00:27:48.140
it is B. If you put in gamma 10
nanoseconds, the inverse of 10

00:27:48.140 --> 00:27:50.940
nanosecond, and the
time is 1 second,

00:27:50.940 --> 00:27:54.910
the excited state amplitude,
the excited stated mixture,

00:27:54.910 --> 00:27:58.620
is 10 to the minus nothing.

00:27:58.620 --> 00:28:00.670
So-- OK.

00:28:00.670 --> 00:28:03.545
If you want to be a
mathematician and say--

00:28:03.545 --> 00:28:04.760
[LAUGHING]

00:28:04.760 --> 00:28:07.860
--there is epsilon 10
to the minus 10, yes.

00:28:07.860 --> 00:28:10.150
Then you can say there is
still a small admixture

00:28:10.150 --> 00:28:11.680
to the excited state.

00:28:11.680 --> 00:28:14.590
But by making it so
extreme-- 10 nanoseconds

00:28:14.590 --> 00:28:19.050
versus a second-- at least
in all practical terms,

00:28:19.050 --> 00:28:22.010
the system is in
the ground state.

00:28:22.010 --> 00:28:23.810
And I think this
should teach you

00:28:23.810 --> 00:28:26.260
what it means if you
have a system which

00:28:26.260 --> 00:28:29.970
is in the superposition of
ground and excited state,

00:28:29.970 --> 00:28:33.060
and after 1 second it
has not emitted a photon.

00:28:33.060 --> 00:28:35.180
I mean--

00:28:35.180 --> 00:28:37.230
Then you would say,
it had its chance.

00:28:37.230 --> 00:28:39.340
It had plenty of
chances to emit,

00:28:39.340 --> 00:28:42.180
but it decided it
doesn't want to emit.

00:28:42.180 --> 00:28:45.130
And that would mean
your 50/50 superposition

00:28:45.130 --> 00:28:47.020
of ground and
excited state means

00:28:47.020 --> 00:28:50.760
the atom decided that
it's in the ground state.

00:28:50.760 --> 00:28:53.200
You should also realize
a 50% superposition

00:28:53.200 --> 00:28:55.630
of ground and
excited state means

00:28:55.630 --> 00:28:59.150
in half, in 50% of the
cases there will never

00:28:59.150 --> 00:29:02.470
be a photon emitted.

00:29:02.470 --> 00:29:04.920
So in other words,
what you should realize

00:29:04.920 --> 00:29:09.580
is if your 50-50% superposition
of ground and excited state,

00:29:09.580 --> 00:29:13.070
that the quantum
evolution of this system

00:29:13.070 --> 00:29:23.470
is-- after a long
time the system

00:29:23.470 --> 00:29:29.680
is definitely positively,
absolutely in the ground state.

00:29:29.680 --> 00:29:33.300
It's always in the ground
state after a long time.

00:29:33.300 --> 00:29:41.970
In 50% of the cases with
emission of a photon,

00:29:41.970 --> 00:29:47.750
in 50% of the cases without
emission of a photon.

00:29:54.360 --> 00:29:56.150
If you have a
radioactive-- ensemble

00:29:56.150 --> 00:30:01.840
of radioactive nuclei-- and
let's say half of the atoms

00:30:01.840 --> 00:30:05.832
are in the excited state
and [INAUDIBLE] and half are

00:30:05.832 --> 00:30:10.430
in the ground state-- and you
send the sample to your friend,

00:30:10.430 --> 00:30:14.820
and your friend waits many,
many, many half times,

00:30:14.820 --> 00:30:17.680
common sense tells you that
all the particles are now

00:30:17.680 --> 00:30:19.870
in the ground state.

00:30:19.870 --> 00:30:22.615
Also only half of them have
decayed, because the other half

00:30:22.615 --> 00:30:24.610
were in the ground
state to begin with.

00:30:24.610 --> 00:30:26.930
I mean this is what
quantum physics tells us.

00:30:26.930 --> 00:30:29.320
This is what a 50/50
superposition is.

00:30:32.640 --> 00:30:35.520
But quantitatively
this is, of course,

00:30:35.520 --> 00:30:41.995
included in this
result-- which magically

00:30:41.995 --> 00:30:45.120
that almost all of you
got right-- namely there

00:30:45.120 --> 00:30:47.430
is a superposition of
ground and excited state,

00:30:47.430 --> 00:30:49.940
but the excited state
amplitude decays.

00:30:49.940 --> 00:30:53.870
And to the limit, in the limit
that the time is much longer

00:30:53.870 --> 00:30:57.110
than the decay time, no matter
what the coefficient initially

00:30:57.110 --> 00:30:59.050
was in front of
the excited state,

00:30:59.050 --> 00:31:01.191
this coefficient
has decayed to 0.

00:31:11.020 --> 00:31:12.902
Any question about that?

00:31:15.790 --> 00:31:20.150
Let me just
emphasize that, again

00:31:20.150 --> 00:31:24.410
in giving you also an example in
the reference, a 0 measurement.

00:31:32.910 --> 00:31:38.360
A 0 measurement modifies
the wave function.

00:31:38.360 --> 00:31:42.620
You can also put it like this,
what the wave function is

00:31:42.620 --> 00:31:44.920
is the best knowledge you
would have about this system.

00:31:44.920 --> 00:31:48.110
The wave function is a way
to predict what happens next,

00:31:48.110 --> 00:31:50.820
and it's the most precise
way to predict it.

00:31:50.820 --> 00:31:53.930
More accurate predictions than
the wave function always cannot

00:31:53.930 --> 00:31:56.910
be made, because of Heisenberg's
uncertainty relation.

00:31:56.910 --> 00:32:00.010
But what happens is,
if you have a 50/50%

00:32:00.010 --> 00:32:02.170
superposition of ground
and excited state,

00:32:02.170 --> 00:32:05.910
and the system has not emitted,
then you would say initially

00:32:05.910 --> 00:32:08.860
my guess was half of the atoms
were excited, half of the atoms

00:32:08.860 --> 00:32:10.460
are in the ground state.

00:32:10.460 --> 00:32:12.770
But if none of them
has decayed for awhile,

00:32:12.770 --> 00:32:15.670
you would say I revise
my estimate now.

00:32:15.670 --> 00:32:18.820
Now I have to assume that
more are in the ground state.

00:32:18.820 --> 00:32:22.660
Because having not decayed means
there is a higher probability

00:32:22.660 --> 00:32:26.260
that the system has actually--
is in the ground state

00:32:26.260 --> 00:32:27.460
to begin with.

00:32:27.460 --> 00:32:32.210
So this is how this way of
dealing with a wave function

00:32:32.210 --> 00:32:35.150
automatically adjusts
for the knowledge

00:32:35.150 --> 00:32:38.090
you have gained
about the system.

00:32:38.090 --> 00:32:40.520
Let me give you another
example which carries home

00:32:40.520 --> 00:32:44.350
the same message, and I take
it from a pedagogical paper

00:32:44.350 --> 00:32:54.888
from Dickey, from American
Journal of Physics, 49, 926,

00:32:54.888 --> 00:32:57.850
