00:38:35.920 --> 00:38:38.630
with simple cases,
namely one photon

00:38:38.630 --> 00:38:40.680
has been emitted or not photon.

00:38:40.680 --> 00:38:42.780
So you want to make
sure that there

00:38:42.780 --> 00:38:50.390
is, at most, one
spontaneous emission event

00:38:50.390 --> 00:38:51.865
during the time delta t.

00:38:54.910 --> 00:38:58.840
So what I'm writing down now
is the total wave function

00:38:58.840 --> 00:39:02.030
of the system plus
the environment.

00:39:02.030 --> 00:39:04.450
And now we can evolve it.

00:39:04.450 --> 00:39:09.370
We can ask what happens?

00:39:09.370 --> 00:39:13.890
What is the wave
function time later?

00:39:13.890 --> 00:39:16.530
This can be exactly done by
time-dependent perturbation

00:39:16.530 --> 00:39:17.870
theory.

00:39:17.870 --> 00:39:20.250
And the result is
that the system

00:39:20.250 --> 00:39:27.290
will be in a superposition
of ground and excited state.

00:39:27.290 --> 00:39:29.110
And we want to calculate
the coefficients

00:39:29.110 --> 00:39:30.540
alpha prime and beta prime.

00:39:35.980 --> 00:39:39.040
And we still have
the vacuum state.

00:39:39.040 --> 00:39:43.150
But then we have the possibility
that a photon has been emitted.

00:39:43.150 --> 00:39:46.490
In that case we are
in the ground state.

00:39:46.490 --> 00:39:49.040
And the direct product
with the environment

00:39:49.040 --> 00:39:53.750
involves now the photon emitted
into a certain direction

00:39:53.750 --> 00:39:58.400
with wave vector k, with
the polarization epsilon.

00:39:58.400 --> 00:40:03.630
And we have coefficients
beta, k epsilon,

00:40:03.630 --> 00:40:07.090
and we have to sum over all
possibilities for the photon

00:40:07.090 --> 00:40:07.680
to be emitted.

00:40:11.220 --> 00:40:15.430
So we call this-- So the wave
function of the total system

00:40:15.430 --> 00:40:17.200
has now two parts.

00:40:17.200 --> 00:40:20.190
It's a wave function,
which I call psi 0.

00:40:20.190 --> 00:40:22.840
This is a wave
function which involves

00:40:22.840 --> 00:40:25.830
no photon in the environment.

00:40:25.830 --> 00:40:28.296
And the wave function
psi 1 involves

00:40:28.296 --> 00:40:29.545
one photon in the environment.

00:40:32.280 --> 00:40:35.190
So this is the [INAUDIBLE],
which seems very natural,

00:40:35.190 --> 00:40:37.330
but it's also-- you
could immediately

00:40:37.330 --> 00:40:39.810
prove that these are the
only possibilities, how

00:40:39.810 --> 00:40:41.700
the system can evolve.

00:40:41.700 --> 00:40:46.221
And we can verify this by using
time-dependent perturbation

00:40:46.221 --> 00:40:46.720
theory.

00:40:57.140 --> 00:40:59.730
It's actually almost
everyone of you

00:40:59.730 --> 00:41:04.310
has seen it in either 8.21 or in
a more basic course on quantum

00:41:04.310 --> 00:41:05.030
physics.

00:41:05.030 --> 00:41:06.690
It's time-dependent
perturbation theory

00:41:06.690 --> 00:41:08.680
for the emission of a photon.

00:41:08.680 --> 00:41:11.920
But usually when you see
those treatments there

00:41:11.920 --> 00:41:18.100
reservoir, the environment,
is not treated as explicitly

00:41:18.100 --> 00:41:21.520
as we do it here.

00:41:21.520 --> 00:41:24.140
The theory where this
is treated exactly

00:41:24.140 --> 00:41:28.210
in this way, how we need it,
is the Viegener Biscoff theory.

00:41:33.080 --> 00:41:35.640
Which is nothing else in
the perturbative approach,

00:41:35.640 --> 00:41:37.890
but it's really a
perturbation theory.

00:41:37.890 --> 00:41:40.920
Not just for the atomic system--
how we sometimes present it

00:41:40.920 --> 00:41:43.720
in a simplified version--
it's perturbation theory

00:41:43.720 --> 00:41:47.060
for the total wave function
of the complete system.

