in the excited state evolves.

00:46:06.030 --> 00:46:09.680
So therefore, what we learn
from perturbation theory,

00:46:09.680 --> 00:46:14.970
that alpha prime and beta prime,
the wave, the coefficients

00:46:14.970 --> 00:46:22.090
of the wave function,
without emission of a photon,

00:46:22.090 --> 00:46:26.240
this evolution of
the wave function

00:46:26.240 --> 00:46:35.140
occurs with a
non-emission Hamiltonian.

00:46:47.000 --> 00:46:49.330
And this non-emission
Hamiltonian

00:46:49.330 --> 00:46:54.560
is our Hamiltonian
for the atomic system.

00:46:54.560 --> 00:46:59.460
But then we have to account
for spontaneous decay,

00:46:59.460 --> 00:47:02.695
and this is done by
this non-emission part.

00:47:06.090 --> 00:47:10.750
So occasionally
you may have heard

00:47:10.750 --> 00:47:13.150
that people wave
their hands and say,

00:47:13.150 --> 00:47:15.820
your system is described
by a Hamiltonian, which

00:47:15.820 --> 00:47:18.550
has an imaginary part for decay.

00:47:18.550 --> 00:47:20.990
And this is sort of
phenomenological.

00:47:20.990 --> 00:47:24.430
This is definitely not
the case, because, even

00:47:24.430 --> 00:47:26.260
if you have a
Hamiltonian like this,

00:47:26.260 --> 00:47:29.740
a pure state would simply
decay and remain a pure state.

00:47:29.740 --> 00:47:32.490
What we are doing
here explicitly

00:47:32.490 --> 00:47:36.410
is we deal with probability
in the correct way.

00:47:36.410 --> 00:47:39.120
Every time the
system can branch out

00:47:39.120 --> 00:47:43.650
into different possibilities,
two different dimensions

00:47:43.650 --> 00:47:47.750
of the density matrix-- one
has probability delta p,

00:47:47.750 --> 00:47:50.610
one has probability
1 minus delta p--

00:47:50.610 --> 00:47:53.330
and it is only the wave
function associated

00:47:53.330 --> 00:47:56.260
with probability 1
minus delta p, which

00:47:56.260 --> 00:47:59.120
evolves with this Hamiltonian.

00:47:59.120 --> 00:48:02.770
So what I'm telling you
is the exact solution

