00:49:24.200 --> 00:49:27.590
of perturbation theory,
is the following.

00:49:27.590 --> 00:49:31.740
We have a time step delta t.

00:49:31.740 --> 00:49:36.290
We compute what
is the probability

00:49:36.290 --> 00:49:43.220
that a photon will be emitted.

00:49:46.090 --> 00:49:53.650
Then we need a ran-- Then we
need a random number generator.

00:49:53.650 --> 00:49:56.630
So we need a number
epsilon, which

00:49:56.630 --> 00:50:03.290
is a random number chosen
in the interval 0 and 1.

00:50:03.290 --> 00:50:11.780
If this random number turns
out to be smaller than delta p,

00:50:11.780 --> 00:50:17.660
then we continue our time
evolution on the computer.

00:50:17.660 --> 00:50:22.170
That psi is now in
the ground state,

00:50:22.170 --> 00:50:24.660
and maybe there is a laser
beam which excites it again.

00:50:24.660 --> 00:50:26.880
And such I will add a few
bells and whistles later.

00:50:29.540 --> 00:50:36.380
Otherwise psi,
our wave function,

00:50:36.380 --> 00:50:42.490
is now the wave function
which is the time evolution

00:50:42.490 --> 00:50:46.310
with a non-emission operator of
the original wave function psi.

00:50:46.310 --> 00:50:48.200
And since we have a
real wave function now

00:50:48.200 --> 00:50:51.837
with probability 1, we have to
re-normalize the wave function

00:50:51.837 --> 00:50:52.670
by this denominator.

00:51:02.490 --> 00:51:05.510
And then we execute
the next time step.

00:51:05.510 --> 00:51:09.720
This means go to 2 and
do the next time step.

00:51:09.720 --> 00:51:12.850
And then you have, so to speak,
if you do it many, many times,

00:51:12.850 --> 00:51:15.980
you get a time direct
trajectory of, so to speak,

00:51:15.980 --> 00:51:17.590
one experiment.

00:51:17.590 --> 00:51:20.510
And then you start again with
your system in a wave function

00:51:20.510 --> 00:51:23.530
psi, and you accumulate
a second experiment.

00:51:23.530 --> 00:51:26.750
And maybe you do it 10,000
times to get enough statistics.

00:51:26.750 --> 00:51:28.820
And then you sum up,
you know, everything

00:51:28.820 --> 00:51:31.130
you want and calculate
all the expectation

00:51:31.130 --> 00:51:34.240
values you want to know
about your quantum system.

00:51:39.260 --> 00:51:50.810
So the claim is that this
method, called quantum Monte

00:51:50.810 --> 00:51:53.760
Carlo wave function
method, is fully

00:51:53.760 --> 00:51:58.260
equivalent to the
optical block equations.

00:51:58.260 --> 00:52:04.080
And I want to prove
it to you by showing

00:52:04.080 --> 00:52:11.850
that, if I take a density
matrix, which is an ensemble

00:52:11.850 --> 00:52:22.080
average, over many
realizations of those quantum

00:52:22.080 --> 00:52:25.510
Monte Carlo trajectories.

00:52:25.510 --> 00:52:30.882
That then this density matrix
follows the differential

00:52:30.882 --> 00:52:32.840
equation, which is your
optical block equation.

00:52:37.670 --> 00:52:40.710
And the proof is shown here.

00:52:40.710 --> 00:52:45.490
So what I told you is the
density matrix after time delta

00:52:45.490 --> 00:52:49.000
t, has now two matrix elements.

00:52:49.000 --> 00:52:51.660
One with probability
delta p, and this

00:52:51.660 --> 00:52:53.190
is-- photon has been emitted.

00:52:53.190 --> 00:52:57.190
System is in the ground state,
with probability 1 minus delta

00:52:57.190 --> 00:52:59.154
p.

00:52:59.154 --> 00:53:04.210
We evolve the quantum state
with a non-emission Hamiltonian.

00:53:07.570 --> 00:53:11.990
And then all what is done
in the next few steps we

00:53:11.990 --> 00:53:14.320
assume that delta t is small.

00:53:14.320 --> 00:53:16.870
We do a Taylor expansion
of the exponent.

00:53:16.870 --> 00:53:19.390
We neglect quadratic
terms in delta t,

00:53:19.390 --> 00:53:20.950
and then we come to this line.

00:53:24.410 --> 00:53:28.640
And if we write this as
rho of t plus delta t,

00:53:28.640 --> 00:53:32.840
minus the original
rho of t, we find

00:53:32.840 --> 00:53:38.130
that this follows differential
equation, which is exactly

00:53:38.130 --> 00:53:40.730
the optical block equations.

00:53:40.730 --> 00:53:43.320
So therefore what we
sort of implemented

00:53:43.320 --> 00:53:45.930
as a form of doing many,
many quantum measurements

00:53:45.930 --> 00:53:50.130
in the environment
is a procedure,

00:53:50.130 --> 00:53:54.155
which is rigorously the
same as the optical block

00:53:54.155 --> 00:53:58.100
equations, which we derived
using a master equation

00:53:58.100 --> 00:53:58.600
approach.

00:54:06.030 --> 00:54:07.310
OK.

00:54:07.310 --> 00:54:11.960
This method is very powerful
for the following reasons.

00:54:11.960 --> 00:54:16.746
If you simulate a density
matrix with, you know,

00:54:16.746 --> 00:54:21.600
an internal states, or external,
internal states-- I should've

00:54:21.600 --> 00:54:23.700
said with in quantum
states, you need

00:54:23.700 --> 00:54:27.320
n times n matrix elements,
which can become quite a memory

00:54:27.320 --> 00:54:29.230
hog for your computer.

00:54:29.230 --> 00:54:33.820
The wave function, at any given
moment, as only n components.

00:54:33.820 --> 00:54:38.150
So therefore there is a
computational advantage

00:54:38.150 --> 00:54:42.360
in using a stochastic
wave function

00:54:42.360 --> 00:54:46.120
approach over simulation
of the density matrix.

00:54:46.120 --> 00:54:48.990
The second thing is that a
lot of people, especially

00:54:48.990 --> 00:54:51.930
experimentalists, like
sort of this approach,

00:54:51.930 --> 00:54:56.150
because it reflects directly
what they do in the experiment.

00:54:56.150 --> 00:55:00.050
And I think it's pretty
clear that with this approach

00:55:00.050 --> 00:55:06.890
you can deal with a great
variety of situations.

00:55:06.890 --> 00:55:10.050
Let me just mention
two obvious extensions.

00:55:10.050 --> 00:55:14.360
One is polarization.

00:55:21.510 --> 00:55:22.500
A photon is detected.

00:55:25.040 --> 00:55:28.570
That means your random number
produced a number epsilon,

00:55:28.570 --> 00:55:31.270
which was smaller than delta p.

00:55:31.270 --> 00:55:41.260
At that point you can create
a second random number,

00:55:41.260 --> 00:55:48.680
which determines if your pull--
if the photon has been detected

00:55:48.680 --> 00:55:51.510
with sigma plus, sigma
minus, or pi polarization.

00:55:54.090 --> 00:55:57.770
Or you can discuss recoil.

00:56:02.270 --> 00:56:07.646
If the photon is-- If
the photon is detected,

00:56:07.646 --> 00:56:11.620
you use-- you throw on
another random function

00:56:11.620 --> 00:56:24.250
generator, which determines what
the k vector of the photon is.

00:56:24.250 --> 00:56:30.730
So what direction each part
k the photon has taken,

00:56:30.730 --> 00:56:34.560
and this determines
now what is the recoil,

00:56:34.560 --> 00:56:37.540
the change in
momentum of your atom.

00:56:37.540 --> 00:56:39.050
So you see, kind
of, you can start

00:56:39.050 --> 00:56:40.840
with an atom at 0 momentum.

00:56:40.840 --> 00:56:43.250
You can see it emits
a photon, and then

00:56:43.250 --> 00:56:45.110
your computer always
makes a choice

00:56:45.110 --> 00:56:46.550
based on the random number.

00:56:46.550 --> 00:56:48.190
And then you say,
OK my photon has now

00:56:48.190 --> 00:56:51.170
received a recoil
kick at 45 degrees.

00:56:51.170 --> 00:56:54.270
Now your wave function of
the photon is such and such,

00:56:54.270 --> 00:56:56.600
and if you add a laser
to the Hamiltonian,

00:56:56.600 --> 00:56:59.430
the recoil may have kicked--
may have Doppler shifted

00:56:59.430 --> 00:57:03.340
the resonance, but everything
is easily taken into account.

00:57:03.340 --> 00:57:05.980
So you see this quantum
Monte Carlo wave function

00:57:05.980 --> 00:57:08.960
method can easily be
extended to describe

00:57:08.960 --> 00:57:11.930
external degrees of freedom,
multiple laser fields, and all

00:57:11.930 --> 00:57:14.750
that.

00:57:14.750 --> 00:57:15.835
Any questions?

