OK.

00:57:22.390 --> 00:57:29.910
Let me now just
generalize the thought,

00:57:29.910 --> 00:57:34.500
but I think you know
already everything about it.

00:57:40.040 --> 00:57:42.760
We talked about the
master equation.

00:57:42.760 --> 00:57:45.820
We talked about the most
general master equation

00:57:45.820 --> 00:57:49.220
in the [INAUDIBLE] platform,
where those operators L

00:57:49.220 --> 00:57:51.420
are the jump operators.

00:57:51.420 --> 00:57:54.960
And the prominent
example for jump operator

00:57:54.960 --> 00:57:57.740
was the signal minus
operator, which

00:57:57.740 --> 00:58:00.780
takes a particle from the
excited state to the ground

00:58:00.780 --> 00:58:01.300
state.

00:58:01.300 --> 00:58:04.810
And this is the jump operator
for spontaneous emission.

00:58:04.810 --> 00:58:06.710
But you may have
many jump operators.

00:58:06.710 --> 00:58:09.770
May be spontaneous emission
of different photons

00:58:09.770 --> 00:58:11.700
with different
polarization and such.

00:58:11.700 --> 00:58:14.690
Or the cavity may lose
a photon, and then we

00:58:14.690 --> 00:58:16.190
have a jump operator
for the cavity.

00:58:16.190 --> 00:58:18.370
We went through that.

00:58:18.370 --> 00:58:22.370
Well that means
now in an exact way

00:58:22.370 --> 00:58:24.200
that the non-emission
Hamiltonian is

00:58:24.200 --> 00:58:27.820
the original Hamiltonian
with an imaginary part, which

00:58:27.820 --> 00:58:29.630
comes because of
those jump operators.

00:58:32.450 --> 00:58:40.680
And the general quantum Monte
Carlo wave function procedure

00:58:40.680 --> 00:58:44.630
is that first you ask,
has something happened?

00:58:44.630 --> 00:58:46.510
Has any jump happened?

00:58:46.510 --> 00:58:50.320
And this gives you the
probability delta p.

00:58:50.320 --> 00:58:55.610
And if-- If no
jump has happened,

00:58:55.610 --> 00:58:57.110
you just do a time
evolution with

00:58:57.110 --> 00:58:59.510
a non-emission Hamiltonian.

00:58:59.510 --> 00:59:10.290
But if a jump has
happened, then the jump

00:59:10.290 --> 00:59:14.690
is now-- the wave function is
projected by the jump operator.

00:59:14.690 --> 00:59:16.320
If you have a sigma
minus operator,

00:59:16.320 --> 00:59:18.160
it takes a particle
to the ground state.

00:59:18.160 --> 00:59:21.230
If you have several operators,
a different jump operator

00:59:21.230 --> 00:59:24.250
may take your particle
to another state.

00:59:24.250 --> 00:59:29.330
And you-- And you then
have a branching ratio

00:59:29.330 --> 00:59:31.500
that you know first
a jump has happened.

00:59:31.500 --> 00:59:34.800
And then the question is,
which jump has happened?

00:59:34.800 --> 00:59:37.110
And you just play the
probabilities game.

00:59:37.110 --> 00:59:39.690
So that you see that the quantum
Monte Carlo wave function

00:59:39.690 --> 00:59:42.400
method can be immediately
be generalized.

00:59:46.430 --> 00:59:53.510
So let me come back
to the special case

00:59:53.510 --> 00:59:56.290
of spontaneous emission.

00:59:56.290 --> 00:59:58.840
In that case, we have
only one jump operator,

00:59:58.840 --> 01:00:00.840
which is sigma minus.

01:00:00.840 --> 01:00:05.140
And the normalization is
the square root of gamma.

01:00:05.140 --> 01:00:12.460
And that actually means that
our quantum trajectory ground

01:00:12.460 --> 01:00:16.160
state, excited state,
is very simple.

01:00:16.160 --> 01:00:21.310
If you start with the system
100% in the excited state,

01:00:21.310 --> 01:00:24.110
it's very trivial what happens.

01:00:24.110 --> 01:00:25.370
Nothing happens.

01:00:25.370 --> 01:00:27.870
But if then the jump
occurs, the particle

01:00:27.870 --> 01:00:30.090
is in the ground state.

01:00:30.090 --> 01:00:34.370
Then nothing happens
then until infinite time.

01:00:34.370 --> 01:00:38.020
You then have to start--
The next trajectory

01:00:38.020 --> 01:00:40.000
you start in the excited state.

01:00:40.000 --> 01:00:44.240
And this time, by chance of
the random number generator,

01:00:44.240 --> 01:00:46.070
the jump happens later.

01:00:46.070 --> 01:00:49.260
Another time the
jump happens earlier.

01:00:49.260 --> 01:00:53.270
And what you then have to
do is, you have to average,

01:00:53.270 --> 01:00:56.200
over all of those
realizations, what

01:00:56.200 --> 01:00:58.830
is the probability
for the particle

01:00:58.830 --> 01:01:00.750
to be in the excited state.

01:01:00.750 --> 01:01:06.080
And this is now your estimator
for the excited state diagonal

01:01:06.080 --> 01:01:08.648
matrix element of
the density matrix.

01:01:08.648 --> 01:01:13.260
And if you-- If you've
written your code correctly,

01:01:13.260 --> 01:01:17.150
you will find that you get a
wonderful exponential decay

01:01:17.150 --> 01:01:18.960
exactly as you have expected.

