our atomic system, the density

01:07:14.140 --> 01:07:18.570
matrix evolves, but the
environment sort of also

01:07:18.570 --> 01:07:19.090
evolves.

01:07:19.090 --> 01:07:22.200
And for instance here,
the unitary time evolution

01:07:22.200 --> 01:07:24.720
has taken the excitation
from the atom,

01:07:24.720 --> 01:07:27.470
and we have emitted a
photon into the environment.

01:07:27.470 --> 01:07:30.370
And you remember we got
the optical block equation

01:07:30.370 --> 01:07:33.190
by doing the partial trace
here, and just focusing

01:07:33.190 --> 01:07:35.650
on the atomic part.

01:07:35.650 --> 01:07:37.930
But now wait a moment.

01:07:37.930 --> 01:07:41.560
If we trace out
the environment, we

01:07:41.560 --> 01:07:45.350
can trace it out in a
different basis set.

01:07:45.350 --> 01:07:47.740
Remember, I showed you the
quantum Monte Carlo wave

01:07:47.740 --> 01:07:49.900
function, we emit a photon.

01:07:49.900 --> 01:07:53.510
But we can, for instance,
detect the photon

01:07:53.510 --> 01:07:55.400
in our gedanken experiment.

01:07:55.400 --> 01:07:57.475
We can detect it with
linear polarization

01:07:57.475 --> 01:07:59.830
or with circular polarization.

01:07:59.830 --> 01:08:03.560
If you have a situation where
you have a-- an s state, which

01:08:03.560 --> 01:08:07.990
decays to a p state, sigma plus
takes you to m equals plus 1,

01:08:07.990 --> 01:08:10.820
sigma minus takes you
to m equals minus 1.

01:08:10.820 --> 01:08:14.330
So therefore, if photon is
emitted in you quantum Monte

01:08:14.330 --> 01:08:17.390
Carlo procedure, you would
say, now the atom mean

01:08:17.390 --> 01:08:19.470
is in the plus 1
state, or now the atom

01:08:19.470 --> 01:08:21.189
is in the minus 1 state.

01:08:21.189 --> 01:08:24.340
But if you detect
linearly polarized light,

01:08:24.340 --> 01:08:26.229
by just putting a
polarizer here--

01:08:26.229 --> 01:08:28.850
and this is a unitary
transformation in front

01:08:28.850 --> 01:08:31.750
of your detector-- you
would no longer project

01:08:31.750 --> 01:08:34.990
the atomic system on
plus 1 at minus 1,

01:08:34.990 --> 01:08:36.760
you would project
it on m equals 0

01:08:36.760 --> 01:08:39.900
or whatever is connected
to the linear polarization

01:08:39.900 --> 01:08:41.790
of the measurement.

01:08:41.790 --> 01:08:44.510
So therefore, if
you simply assume

01:08:44.510 --> 01:08:46.720
that something has been
dumped in the environment,

01:08:46.720 --> 01:08:49.359
and can be used for
measurement, there

01:08:49.359 --> 01:08:52.680
are many ways, many
unitary transformations,

01:08:52.680 --> 01:08:56.580
what you can do to the
information, to the energy,

01:08:56.580 --> 01:08:59.609
to the photons, which have been
dumped into the environment.

01:08:59.609 --> 01:09:04.640
And each of them will lead to
a very different trajectory

01:09:04.640 --> 01:09:07.590
in your quantum
Monte Carlo system.

01:09:07.590 --> 01:09:09.870
So therefore if you
just dump the photons

01:09:09.870 --> 01:09:12.390
and not measure them,
you have equal rights

01:09:12.390 --> 01:09:15.990
to assume that your quantum
Monte Carlo wave function jumps

01:09:15.990 --> 01:09:19.479
to states which correspond
to a circular basis,

01:09:19.479 --> 01:09:23.540
or jump to states which
correspond to linear basis.

01:09:23.540 --> 01:09:26.649
And there's many,
many possibilities.

01:09:26.649 --> 01:09:33.649
But each of those possibilities
is 100% correct unravelling

01:09:33.649 --> 01:09:35.970
of the density matrix.

01:09:35.970 --> 01:09:40.330
And if you just do it right,
assume that the measurement is

01:09:40.330 --> 01:09:43.640
done in a certain basis, and
you're consistent with it,

01:09:43.640 --> 01:09:47.490
you will 100% correctly
describe the time evolution

01:09:47.490 --> 01:09:48.670
of your atomic system.

