01:19:51.140 --> 01:19:55.220
of your atomic system, in which
basis you measure the photon.

01:19:55.220 --> 01:19:58.870
So the evolution of the
atomic system itself--

01:19:58.870 --> 01:20:05.320
at least when you averaged--
is unaffected by the basis.

01:20:05.320 --> 01:20:08.040
However if you make a
coincidence measurement,

01:20:08.040 --> 01:20:10.430
that you say your atoms
which has emitted,

01:20:10.430 --> 01:20:12.700
is still flying through
your vacuum chamber,

01:20:12.700 --> 01:20:14.540
and now you figure
out the photon

01:20:14.540 --> 01:20:17.150
is emitted as circularly
polarized light.

01:20:17.150 --> 01:20:20.590
Then of course you know that
this atom, which is still

01:20:20.590 --> 01:20:23.592
available, has emitted
circularly polarized light.

01:20:23.592 --> 01:20:25.800
And then you have actually
obtained extra information

01:20:25.800 --> 01:20:27.540
about your atom.

01:20:27.540 --> 01:20:29.850
In other words, the
photon in the atom

01:20:29.850 --> 01:20:32.760
was entangled, like a Bell pair.

01:20:32.760 --> 01:20:36.020
And if you now do a measurement
on one part of the Bell pair,

01:20:36.020 --> 01:20:38.190
you know more about
the other part.

01:20:38.190 --> 01:20:40.190
But this is just how
quantum physics works.

01:20:40.190 --> 01:20:42.870
If you don't use this
information for anything,

01:20:42.870 --> 01:20:46.840
then you could have-- you
could have as well not measured

01:20:46.840 --> 01:20:47.685
the polarization.

01:20:47.685 --> 01:20:51.707
And it would have no effect
on the atomic density matrix.

